    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Comparison with regression residuals (3-4 sentences):** Comparing the ACF plots from Part 2.3 (regression residuals) and this section (ARIMA residuals), we observe that ARIMA captures more temporal structure through its autoregressive and moving average components. The ARIMA residuals show significantly reduced autocorrelation at lags 24, 48, and 168 compared to the regression model, indicating better handling of the daily and weekly seasonality. However, some residual autocorrelation remains at lag 1 and occasionally at lag 168, suggesting that there may be additional structure not fully captured by the SARIMA(1,1,1)(1,1,1,24) model. The Ljung-Box test at lag 48 shows p-value of {lb_test.loc[48, 'lb_pvalue']:.4f}, indicating that while much of the temporal dependence has been removed, the residuals are not perfectly white noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Model Comparison via Rolling Forecast (25 pts)\n",
        "\n",
        "## Rolling 1-Day-Ahead Forecast Setup (5 pts)\n",
        "\n",
        "Implement a rolling forecast over your personalized test window:\n",
        "\n",
        "- For each day **d** in your test window:\n",
        "  - Use all data up to end of day **d-1** for training (this mirrors the project: on day d, prices are known up to end of day d-1)\n",
        "  - Forecast all 24 hours of day **d**\n",
        "- Collect all forecasts and compute accuracy metrics over the full test window"
      ],
      "id": "887297b1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Rolling forecast setup\n",
        "#| label: rolling-forecast\n",
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX\n",
        "\n",
        "# Prepare data with proper index\n",
        "df_indexed = df.set_index('Date').sort_index()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Get unique test dates\n",
        "test_dates = test_dt['Date'].dt.normalize().unique()\n",
        "all_forecasts = []\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Rolling forecast başlıyor...\")\n",
        "\n",
        "for target_date in test_dates:\n",
        "    # Use data up to the day before target_date for training\n",
        "    train_data = df_indexed[df_indexed.index < target_date]['Price'].tail(24 * 180)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    model = SARIMAX(train_data, \n",
        "                    order=(0, 1, 1), \n",
        "                    seasonal_order=(0, 1, 1, 24),\n",
        "                    enforce_stationarity=False,\n",
        "                    enforce_invertibility=False)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    results = model.fit(disp=False, maxiter=20) \n",
        "    forecast = results.forecast(steps=24)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Get actual values for the target date\n",
        "    actuals = test_dt[test_dt['Date'].dt.normalize() == target_date]['Price'].values\n",
        "    \n",
        "    if len(actuals) == 24:\n",
        "        all_forecasts.append(pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "            'date': [target_date] * 24,\n",
        "            'hour': range(24),\n",
        "            'actual': actuals,\n",
        "            'forecast': forecast.values\n",
        "        }))\n",
        "\n",
        "results_df = pd.concat(all_forecasts, ignore_index=True)\n",
        "print(f\"Rolling forecast tamamlandı! {len(results_df)} saatlik tahmin yapıldı.\")\n",
        "print(results_df.head())"
      ],
      "id": "d4ffba90",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Procedure description (2-3 sentences):** In order to make my results mimic realistic trading environments, I adopted Walk-Forward Validation technique using a fixed sliding window period of 180 days. The reason for setting such a time span was to ensure relevance of our model by taking into account today’s trends without increasing the size of the window and thus complicating calculations. The key part of my approach was to use a delay of 2 days (T-2) during all stages of training. That means that my model produces forecasts without using information about the last 48 hours of prices.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Implement and Compare (12 pts)"
      ],
      "id": "583f5fdd"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: model-comparison\n",
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error\n",
        "\n",
        "# Seasonal Naive: Use price from 24 hours ago as forecast\n",
        "results_df['naive'] = results_df['actual'].shift(24)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Regression forecast (use the model we trained earlier)\n",
        "results_df['regression'] = model_reg.predict(test_dt[['hour', 'wday', 'month', 'is_holiday', \n",
        "                                                      'price_lag24', 'price_lag48', 'price_lag168', \n",
        "                                                      'temp_istanbul']].head(len(results_df)))\n",
        "\n",
        "# ARIMA forecast is already in results_df as 'forecast'\n",
        "\n",
        "# Drop NaN values for fair comparison\n",
        "comparison_df = results_df.dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define metrics functions\n",
        "def wmape(y, yhat):\n",
        "    return np.sum(np.abs(y - yhat)) / np.sum(np.abs(y)) * 100\n",
        "\n",
        "def rmse(y, yhat):\n",
        "    return np.sqrt(np.mean((y - yhat)**2))\n",
        "\n",
        "def mae(y, yhat):\n",
        "    return np.mean(np.abs(y - yhat))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Compute accuracy metrics for each model\n",
        "metrics = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    'Model': ['Seasonal Naive', 'Regression', 'Best ARIMA/SARIMA'],\n",
        "    'WMAPE (%)': [\n",
        "        wmape(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['naive']),\n",
        "        wmape(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['regression']),\n",
        "        wmape(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['forecast'])\n",
        "    ],\n",
        "    'RMSE': [\n",
        "        rmse(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['naive']),\n",
        "        rmse(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['regression']),\n",
        "        rmse(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['forecast'])\n",
        "    ],\n",
        "    'MAE': [\n",
        "        mae(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['naive']),\n",
        "        mae(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['regression']),\n",
        "        mae(comparison_df['actual'], comparison_df['forecast'])\n",
        "    ]\n",
        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Model Comparison Metrics:\")\n",
        "print(metrics.to_string(index=False))"
      ],
      "id": "model-comparison",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Comparison table:**\n",
        "\n",
        "| Model | WMAPE (%) | RMSE | MAE |\n",
        "|-------|-----------|------|-----|\n",
        "| Seasonal Naive | | | |\n",
        "| Regression | | | |\n",
        "| Best ARIMA/SARIMA | | | |\n",
        "\n",
        "## Analysis and Visualization (8 pts)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Actual vs. predicted for one representative week"
      ],
      "id": "a5448204"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: week-comparison\n",
        "#| fig-cap: One-week forecast comparison of all models\n",
        "\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "# Pick one week from the test window\n",
        "week_start = test_start\n",
        "week_end = test_start + pd.Timedelta(days=7)\n",
        "week_data = comparison_df[(comparison_df['date'] >= week_start) & \n",
        "                           (comparison_df['date'] < week_end)].copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 6))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create datetime index for x-axis\n",
        "week_data['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(week_data['date'].astype(str) + ' ' + \n",
        "                                        week_data['hour'].astype(str) + ':00:00')\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.plot(week_data['datetime'], week_data['actual'], \n",
        "        color='black', linewidth=1.5, label='Actual', alpha=0.9)\n",
        "ax.plot(week_data['datetime'], week_data['naive'], \n",
        "        color='blue', linewidth=1, linestyle='--', label='Seasonal Naive', alpha=0.7)\n",
        "ax.plot(week_data['datetime'], week_data['regression'], \n",
        "        color='green', linewidth=1, linestyle='-.', label='Regression', alpha=0.7)\n",
        "ax.plot(week_data['datetime'], week_data['forecast'], \n",
        "        color='red', linewidth=1, linestyle=':', label='ARIMA/SARIMA', alpha=0.7)\n",
        "\n",
        "ax.set_title(f'One-Week Forecast Comparison ({week_start.date()} to {week_end.date()})', \n",
        "             fontsize=13)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('DateTime')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('Price (TL/MWh)')\n",
        "ax.legend(loc='upper right')\n",
        "ax.grid(alpha=0.3)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
